			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2516">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>For months now, I have more or less shuddered at the arrival of <strong>The Sun</strong>. Some issues go unread, because I just can&rsquo;t lower myself back into the pit with the junkies and winos (having spent a little time there myself).</p>

<p>But when the May issue came, I was delighted to see a story about Ram Dass [&ldquo;<a href="/article/1982">One Hand Clapping</a>,&rdquo; by Sy Safransky]. He was an early teacher of mine, a guide on the long and winding road of spiritual seeking. That Ram Dass is able to maintain his humor and lightness after such a debilitating stroke is a teaching for us all. No matter what happens in his life, it seems, his purpose will always be to guide and inspire.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Sukoshi Rice<br>Blairsville, Georgia</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2517">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>When I opened the May 1998 issue of <strong>The Sun</strong> and saw Ram Dass&rsquo;s wonderful face, I got worried. Having heard about his stroke, I thought, <em>What if he&rsquo;s died and nobody has told me?</em> I skipped to the end, just to see. Nope. He was still alive. So I went back and started from the beginning. I already knew all of Sy Safransky&rsquo;s stories about Ram Dass, but it didn&rsquo;t matter. With Ram Dass, somehow the old stories always seem new.</p>

<p>In the June 1998 issue, a very different photo caught my eye. Having berated <strong>The Sun</strong> in the past for publishing a photograph of a tiny infant about to be circumcised at a bris ceremony (as if it were OK to cut someone&rsquo;s genitals without his permission), I was overjoyed to see the full-frontal shot of a gloriously intact nude man on the inside back cover.</p>

<p>The photographs mentioned above are available as PDFs only. Download the <a href="http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issue/pdf/269.pdf">May 1998 issue</a> here, <a href="http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issue/pdf/270.pdf">June 1998 here</a>, and <a href="http://www.thesunmagazine.org/issue/pdf/265.pdf">January 1998 here</a>.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Cat Saunders<br>Seattle, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2518">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Sy Safransky&rsquo;s &ldquo;One Hand Clapping&rdquo; reminded me of the powerful influence that Ram Dass has had on my life. I would like to point out, however, that one significant aspect of Ram Dass&rsquo;s life is often glossed over or not openly discussed: his sexuality. In<em> Gay Soul: Finding the Heart of Gay Spirit and Nature,</em> by Mark Thompson, Ram Dass tells the author that it was not only his experiments with drugs that got him fired from Harvard, as Safransky says, but also his sexual encounters with young men:</p>

<p><strong>Ram Dass:</strong> Harvard started to get so freaked about the drugs [Timothy Leary and I] were using that they asked us to stop doing any research using undergraduates .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. because it was too risky. But I had all these relationships with young men whom I really wanted to turn on with. And it had nothing to do with research; it was my personal life, so I went ahead. It turned out there was another student who was very jealous of this .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. and he created a huge expos&eacute;.</p>

<p><strong>Mark Thompson:</strong> So it was gay eros and not LSD that got you thrown out of Harvard?</p>

<p><strong>Ram Dass:</strong> It was a combination of all of those things. In a way, LSD had given me the license to be what I am .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. to say I didn&rsquo;t want to hide anymore.</p>

<p>In no way does Ram Dass&rsquo;s physically loving men detract from his remarkable spiritual journey.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jerry Button<br>Portland, Oregon</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2519">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I enjoyed &ldquo;One Hand Clapping,&rdquo; and was drawn along comfortably by the story &mdash; until I read that Ram Dass was bisexual. Whereas, in the past, I might have stopped reading, this time I thought about my &ldquo;spiritual homework,&rdquo; and, as if my hand were guided by some mysterious, uncontrollable force, I wrote a check to the Ram Dass Medical Fund.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Carl Berk<br>Clinton Correctional Facility<br />Dannemora, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2507">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I am a longtime subscriber to <strong>The Sun</strong> and especially enjoyed the long essay about Ram Dass in the May 1998 issue [&ldquo;<a href="/article/1982">One Hand Clapping</a>,&rdquo; Sy Safransky]. I left that issue out and encouraged my family (including my children) to read it. When the June issue arrived, I left it out, too. I was surprised to find later that the June issue contained explicit material, in particular, &ldquo;<a href="/article/1993">To Be a Sexual Son</a>,&rdquo; by David Steinberg. I wish you would indicate on the cover when the magazine contains subject matter not suited for children.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Girija Brilliant<br>San Francisco, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
